prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Receiver(s): Band 6 (221 GHz)
Angular Resolution: ~0.5" at Band 6. The ACA is not needed for these observations since the sources are small.
Spectral Resolution: FDM mode with spectral averaging of 16 for a total bandwidth of 4x1875 MHz and a resolution of 7.813 MHz. This setup gives the same data rates as TDM though with a factor of 4 better resolution (~10 km/s versus 40 km/s).
Continuum (Band 6) Sensitivity: In Cycle 2, up to 150 sources may be observed in one science goal, provided the sources are less than 10" apart. In the sky observable by ALMA, we find the 10" region that has the largest number of quasars having GALEX, SDSS, UKIDSS and WISE data. This region contains 89 quasars.
The dust continuum flux density can be estimated via Scoville 2012 (equation 8.26). This equation relates the mass of the ISM, redshift, frequency of observations and luminosity distance to the dust continuum flux density. The flux density is lowest at z~1 and increases at lower and higher redshift. Therefore, we make minimum flux density estimates using the minimum redshift of our sample, z=1.5. We calculate the mass of the ISM by scaling the black hole mass by the Mbulge-to-Mbh ratio and gas-to-stellar mass ratio. The bulge mass is chosen to be consistent with Mbh-Mbulge relation, where the minimum expected black hole mass is chosen to be 10^8 solar masses. We use the bulge mass as a proxy for the host galaxy stellar mass. High mass systems have lower gas to stellar mass ratios. Using a gas to stellar mass ratio of 3, we estimate the minimum ISM mass to be 2x10^11 solar masses. Therefore, these sources should have S230GHz > 2.1 mJy. We aim to get a S/N ~ 20, though because of our conservative estimates on the flux density we will likely get much higher S/N.
We set LO1 (227 GHz) to maximize the chance of the CO J=7-6 transition falling in one of the sidebands (~25% of our targets, <z>=2.52) in Band 6. Our primary goal is to characterize the cool dust continuum of quasars. However, to ensure maximum scientific output we request FDM mode with spectral averaging of 16 which gives the same data rates (also, aggregate bandwidth sensitivity and total time requested) as TDM though with a factor of 4 better resolution (~10 km/s versus 40 km/s).
Band 6 Observing Time: For Band 6, the ALMA sensitivity calculator, assuming thirty-four 12-m antennas and dual polarization, predicts 1.82 minutes integration per source to reach a 1 sigma = 0.1 mJy in the aggregate band. Each science goal of 44 sources would require about 2.70 hours of on-source integration, and 1.55 hours of calibration and 62.77 minutes of overhead for a total of 5.29 hours. Our overheads are ~20% of the total time requested, which is within the limit (<30%) suggested in the ALMA Cycle 2 Proposer's Guide.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to use ALMA to test models predicting how active supermassive black holes and their host galaxies co-evolve in the most luminous systems at high redshift. We are requesting 5.3 hours of time in Band 6 to measure the rest-frame sub-millimeter spectral slopes for a complete sample of 89 luminous quasars with 1.5 < z < 3.5. We will use state-of-the-art techniques to determine the fundamental quasar properties (Mbh, Lbol, and L/LEdd) from ancillary ultraviolet, optical, and infrared data that exist for all sample members. Combining these with new observations from ALMA will allow us to measure the mass of dust and the global star formation rates in the host galaxy. A comparison of these properties will constitute a test of current galaxy evolution models which predict that accretion rates in quasars are related to star formation in their host galaxies due mergers which are thought to fuel both processes. Furthermore, we will generate mean quasar spectral energy distributions that will be made publicly available to the community. This will be the first such data product that does not simply ``connect the dots'' between infrared and radio detections.
